rties. She shows us the different opportunities for economic and political participation that exist for them, explaining why young Egyptians may choose to either mobilize against or—surprisingly—in support of the regime. Sika underscores how youth in Egypt have been regarded as both the “hope of the nation” and a “threat to the nation.” Youth in Egypt shines a light on the rising generation of young people that represents Egypt's future and also has significant implications for the broader Middle East and North Africa region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aYouthzEgypt. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAl-Sisi.  aAuthoritarianism.  aCivic Engagement.  aCivic Participation.  aCivil Society Organizations.  aCivil Society.  aCo-optation Strategies.  aCo-optation.  aDepoliticization.  aDisengagement.  aEducation.  aEgypt Political History.  aEgypt.  aEmployment Opportunities.  aEntrepreneurship.  aGender.  aJanuary 25 Uprising.  aMENA.  aMarginalization.  aMedia.  aMobilization.  aMubarak.  aNasser.  aNeoliberalism.  aPolitical Economy.  aPolitical Engagement.  aPolitical Parties.  aPolitical Transitions.  aPoverty.  aRepression.  aRevolutionary Youth.  aYouth Contention.  aYouth Precarity.  aYouth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2023 Englishz978311131925408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2023z9783111318677oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 202